                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       Subscriber growth buoys Airtel bottom line
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                                        
	New Delhi, Oct. 31: Bharti Airtel today posted a 42 per cent increase in revenues at Rs 9,020 crore for the second quarter ended September 2008 against Rs 6,337 crore in the corresponding period last year.        
	Net profit for the quarter under review jumped 27 per cent on the back of subscriber additions to Rs 2,046 crore from Rs 1,613 crore a year ago.        
	Bharti added 8.1 million mobile phone users to increase its subscriber base to 77.5 million by the end of September.        
	Customer growth did not depend on few towns or cities. Its coming from every part of India, said Akhil Gupta, deputy group chief executive of Bharti Enterprises.        
	Tata Motors skids        
	Tata Motors today reported a 34.1 per cent decline in profit after tax for the quarter ended September 30 at Rs 346.99 crore against Rs 526.84 crore during the same period last year because of higher raw material costs and a notional foreign exchange loss of Rs 285.02 crore.        
	Although revenues rose 6.1 per cent to Rs 7,078.85 crore, sales of passenger cars and utility vehicles fell 13.4 per cent to 47,151 units from 54,474 units in the year-ago period.        
	According to Tata Motors, the notional exchange valuation loss of Rs 285.02 crore reflected the volatility in foreign exchange rates affecting its long-term funds raised through issue of foreign currency convertible instruments.        
	R-Com show        
	Reliance Communications (R-Com) has posted a 17.31 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 1,530.78 crore for the second quarter ended September 30.        
	The consolidated revenue was up 23.30 per cent at Rs 5,645 crore during the quarter under review.         
	Suzlon loss        
	Suzlon Energy registered a 95.22 per cent decline in net profit at Rs 16.98 crore for the second quarter ended September 30 compared with a net profit of Rs 355.56 crore over the corresponding period a year ago.        
	The wind energy major has scrapped its plans to set up tower manufacturing facilities in the country and reduced its capex by Rs 669 crore, chairman and managing director Tulsi Tanti said.        
	Oil PSUs in the red        
	Three state-owned oil companies have reported net losses in the second quarter ended September 30 even after receiving oil bonds from the government.        
	Indian Oil Corporation (IOC) recorded a net loss of Rs 7,047.13 crore for the second quarter against a net profit of Rs 3,817.75 crore in the same period last year.         
	Hindustan Petroleum Corporation suffered a net loss of Rs 3,218.92 crore for the second quarter compared with a net profit of Rs 853 crore in the year-ago period. Bharat Petroleum Corporations net loss stood at Rs 2,625.17 crore against a profit of Rs 1,038.16 crore in the September quarter of last fiscal.        
	Meanwhile, GAIL (India) today signed an agreement with IOC to set up a Rs 10,000-crore petrochemical plant of 3,00,000-tonne capacity at Barauni in Bihar.                                                                                                                                     
